    "summary": "Agree with profile, one addition proposed",
    "content": "**AGREE**, with one addition:\n\n**ADD: 7. Sensitivity to the performative/experimental dimension of the text.**\n\nThis is the lesson from our philosophical experiments discussion. The translator must understand that certain passages are not descriptions to be rendered accurately but *performances to be reproduced effectively*. The Sisyphus-to-cat graduation, the Dao-De-Ren-Yi-Li reversal, the magic book narratives -- these passages succeed or fail based on whether the English reader undergoes the same experiential restructuring as the Chinese reader. A translator who treats every passage as \"source text to be rendered into target text\" will miss this dimension. The translator needs to be someone who can ask: \"Does this English version *do* to the reader what the Chinese version does?\"\n\nThis is not the same as literary sensibility (point 3), which concerns aesthetic quality of prose. It is closer to what a playwright or game designer does: constructing an experience through sequential disclosure. The translator models listed (Watson, Graham, Ziporyn) are excellent for philosophical translation but are not specifically known for this performative sensitivity. If we are looking for an additional model, consider translators who have worked on texts that are explicitly designed to transform the reader -- for instance, translators of Zen koans (e.g., Thomas Cleary) or Kierkegaard (e.g., Howard and Edna Hong, who had to preserve Kierkegaard's indirect communication method).\n\nOn the other 6 points: all correct and well-prioritized. The category theory literacy (point 4) is essential and non-negotiable for Essays 6-7. The register shift capability (point 5) is correctly identified -- the magic book examples in particular require a translator who can write playful, almost children's-literature prose in one paragraph and precise mathematical exposition in the next.\n\nNo removals.\n"
  }
